observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following corrective measures:

Inventory Committee, in compliance to the provisions of the new GAM for LGUs Volume II:

conduct the physical count of all municipal properties and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Land and Land Improvements,  Report on the Physical Count of Other Public Infrastructure, Report on the Physical Count of Buildings and Structures and Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network; and (ii) submit copy of the inventory reports to the Audit Team for verification and audit;

Municipal Accountant:

maintain the following ledger cards in accordance with Sections 16 to 21 of the GAM for LGUs Volume II: (a) Land and Land Improvements Ledger Card, (b) Local Road Network Ledger Card, (c) Other Public Infrastructure Ledger Card, (d) Buildings and Structures Ledger Card, (e) Equipment Ledger Card;  (f) Other Property, and Plant and Equipment Ledger Card; 

provide depreciation for depreciable PPE with aggregate cost of ₱8,591,138.12 in accordance with Paragraphs 43 and 71 of IPSAS 17; 

transfer to the appropriate PPE accounts the costs of three completed infrastructure projects totaling ₱10,482,059.23 and thereafter compute and recognize its depreciation expense; and 



transfer to the General Fund the cost of completed projects booked as PPE under the Trust Fund books totaling ₱8,591,138.12; and


Municipal Treasurer, as the acting GSO maintain complete property cards with complete information pursuant to Section 61 of the GAM for LGUs, Volume II.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor, as the head of the agency, (a) ensure that the projects charged against the 20% Development Fund partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures pursuant to Section 2.3 of the DBM-DILG JMC 2017-1;
Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Budget Officer strictly adhere with the mandates of R.A. No. 7160 and ensure that the unexpended balances of appropriations for non-capital outlay are reverted to the general fund and shall thereafter be available for expenditure only through a subsequent enactment;
Municipal Mayor, thru the BAC Chairperson submit a written explanation on the inconsistency regarding the item description/specification noted in the supporting documents for the procurement of nylon fish nets amounting to ₱196,000.00; and
Municipal Accountant, as part of her internal audit duties, ensure the propriety, accuracy and consistency of information contained in the supporting documents before processing and certifying the disbursement vouchers.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor, as agency head, ensure that the winning contractors have posted the required performance security before the contract signing;
Municipal Accountant and the BAC Secretariat immediately submit to the Audit Team the lacking documents to facilitate technical evaluation and validation of the projects;
Municipal Accountant (i) check the regularity and completeness of supporting documents prescribed under Section 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 before processing claims for payments and ensure compliance with 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to establish the legality, validity and propriety of the disbursements; (ii) ensure that claims for advance payments are duly supported with irrevocable standby letter of credit of equivalent value from a commercial bank, a bank guarantee or a surety bond callable upon demand, issued by a surety or insurance company duly licensed by the Insurance Commission and confirmed by the PE; and
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer compute and impose liquidated damages against the contractors of infrastructure projects that were completed beyond contract expiry date pursuant to Section 8 of the Contract Implementation Guidelines for the Procurement of Infrastructure Projects.

We recommended that the:

LCE, through the Municipal Accountant, (a) serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted; (b) ensure that all concerned officers and employees strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 97-002, P.D. No. 1445, R.A. No. 7160 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; and (c) see that internal controls are in place to ensure proper segregation of duties and functions; 

Disbursing Officers/ SDOs submit liquidations of the CAs within the prescribed period provided in COA Circular No. 97-002;

Municipal Accountant:

prepare the schedule of all receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers every quarter;

submit the duly signed Statement of Cash Advances and Liquidations of Rosemila G. Dingson and MT Marlo B. Friolo as of December 31, 2018 and June 30, 2019;

discontinue certifying cash advance vouchers of elective officials and the Municipal Treasurer unless the purpose of grant is for their official travelling expenses; and

strictly monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances to ensure that no additional cash advance is granted unless the previous one have been duly liquidated and accounted for.

We recommended that the:

Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit to the Audit Team duly authenticated copies of the MOA/Trust Agreement with the PGP pertaining to the fund transfer and other documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001;

Municipal Accountant (i) make the necessary adjustments to correct the entries made for the fund transferred to PGP; and (ii) maintain SL therefor to ensure proper monitoring of its utilization including the implementation of the project;

Members of the SB ensure that all changes in the annual budget such as re-appropriation of savings or re-programming of discontinued projects or abandonment of PPAs to any item of expenditure under any class or to any new item of expenditure not included in the annual budget are covered by an appropriation ordinance or supplemental budget and submit the same to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for review; and

Municipal Budget Officer certify the existence of valid appropriations only for expenditures supported with supplemental budget or appropriation ordinance duly authorized by the Sanggunian.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, as the head of the agency:

submit the Municipality’s SWMP to the PCSD for the latter’s approval;

cause the establishment of a sanitary landfill meeting the requirements of Sections 40, 41 and 42 of R.A. No. 9003;

direct the SWM focal person to have the MRFs properly labelled and conduct vegetation control to make them functional in receiving biodegradable wastes for composting and mixed non-biodegradable wastes for final segregation, re-use and recycling; and

ensure that all waste transport vehicles used by the LGU are compliant with the requirements of Section 24 of R.A. No. 9003.

1. LCE, through the Municipal Accountant, (a) serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted; (b) ensure that all concerned officers and employees strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 97-002, P.D. No. 1445, R.A. No. 7160 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; and (c) see that internal controls are in place to ensure proper segregation of duties and functions;
2. Disbursing Officers/ SDOs submit liquidations of the CAs within the prescribed period provided in COA Circular No. 97-002;
3. Municipal Accountant:
 prepare the schedule of all receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers every quarter;
 submit the duly signed Statement of Cash Advances and Liquidations of Rosemila G. Dingson and MT Marlo B. Friolo as of December 31, 2018 and June 30, 2019;
 discontinue certifying cash advance vouchers of elective officials and the Municipal Treasurer unless the purpose of grant is for their official travelling expenses; and
 strictly monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances to ensure that no additional cash advance is granted unless the previous one have been duly liquidated and accounted for.

We recommended that the:
1. Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit to the Audit Team duly authenticated copies of the MOA/Trust Agreement with the PGP pertaining to the fund transfer and other documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001;
2. Municipal Accountant (i) make the necessary adjustments to correct the entries made for the fund transferred to PGP; and (ii) maintain SL therefor to ensure proper monitoring of its utilization including the implementation of the project;
3. Members of the SB ensure that all changes in the annual budget such as re-appropriation of savings or re-programming of discontinued projects or abandonment of PPAs to any item of expenditure under any class or to any new item of expenditure not included in the annual budget are covered by an appropriation ordinance or supplemental budget and submit the same to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for review; and
4. Municipal Budget Officer certify the existence of valid appropriations only for expenditures supported with supplemental budget or appropriation ordinance duly authorized by the Sanggunian.

The management committed to comply with the audit recommendations. Regarding the erroneous recording of the fund transfer in the LGU books, the Municipal Accountant will make adjusting entries to correct the recording of the fund transfer.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, as the head of the agency:
a. submit the Municipality’s SWMP to the PCSD for the latter’s approval;
b. cause the establishment of a sanitary landfill meeting the requirements of Sections 40, 41 and 42 of R.A. No. 9003;
c. direct the SWM focal person to have the MRFs properly labelled and conduct vegetation control to make them functional in receiving biodegradable wastes for composting and mixed non-biodegradable wastes for final segregation, re-use and recycling; and
d. ensure that all waste transport vehicles used by the LGU are compliant with the requirements of Section 24 of R.A. No. 9003.

During the audit exit conference, the Municipal Mayor commented that the only problem with the installed MRFs is the waste segregation which is the primary responsibility of the barangays. She suggested that the said matter should be referred to the Punong Barangays for immediate action. With regard to the SWM Plan, the LGU is still in the process of preparing the said plan. The LGU had already conducted the Waste Analysis and Characterization Study (WACS) and had already identified a potential sanitary landfill site.

We have recommended that Management:

Require the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1;
Require the maintenance of complete and accurate Equipment Ledger Cards/ PPELC for each inventory item pursuant to Section 488 (d) of the GAAM and the NGAS in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;
Require the reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records after the physical count;
Physical Inventory Reports shall be submitted to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Accounting Office and Property Unit, respectively;
Require the renewal of Memorandum Receipt (MR) of Equipment every January of the third year after issue in accordance with Section 492 of GAAM Vol. 1; and
Comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.
